Class AsyncDataHandler

java.lang.Object
  org.xml.sax.helpers.DefaultHandler
      com.unvired.sync.in.AsyncDataHandler
All Implemented Interfaces:

Direct Known Subclasses:
AsyncJSONDataHandler, AsyncXMLDataHandler
public abstract class AsyncDataHandler
extends org.xml.sax.helpers.DefaultHandler

AsyncDataHandler handles asynchronous application data. AsyncDataHandler parses the incoming asynchronous responses and saves the data. Only data in IBXML format can be handled by the AsyncDataHandler. The logic for saving is based on the message request type. RQST - The response can have only 1 BE. This is in response to the request sent by the application. Parse the data into header and item structures. Delete the existing header and item structures in the DB based on LID in the sent items object. For the incoming header use the same LID from the sent items object and save the header and item structures. Delete the entry from sent items. PULL - Server can push multiple BEs to the application. Server can also indicate if only these pushed data should be retained on the device or the data already on the device should also be retained. Parse the data into header and item structures. Insert / update all the headers and item data structures. If the meta data indicates deletion is required then delete all data that is not part of the incoming list and those that are in OBJECT_STATUS.GLOBAL or OBJECT_STATUS.NONE. If the meta data indicates deletion is not required then no deletion is performed. PUSH - Server can push multiple BEs to the application. Parse the data into header and item structures. Insert / update all the headers and item data structures. QUERY - Mobile application can place an asynchronous request for data. Server can respond with multiple BEs. Parse the data into header and item structures. Insert / update all the headers and item data structures. In all above cases before inserting or updating data the header data structure is checked for conflict. If there is a conflict between the incoming data and the data stored on the device (due to local changes in the application on the device) then the conflict handler registered by the application is called. No action is taken by the framework for conflict.
